In this project, you used web-scraping to collect information from Airbnb to determine whether
hosts complied with San Francisco’s rental laws. These regulations rely on multiple parties to
maintain accountability: hosts must register with the city’s planning office, Airbnb must
accurately display policy numbers, and third parties scrape data and file complaints.
The questions below ask you to reflect on whether the current system effectively holds hosts
and platforms accountable, along with the legal and ethical issues associated with
web-scraping.


Do you think this current system provides adequate accountability around short-term
rentals in San Francisco? In your response, describe why you believe the system is
adequate or inadequate. If you believe the system is inadequate, discuss a possible
change in actions required to improve accountability in this system. You may refer to the
SWE Code of Ethics as you think through your response.

I think the current system provides some level of adequacy especially when it comes to allowing 
multiple parties, like hosts, Airbnb, and third parties, to contribute to maintaining accountability. 
However, to me, the system fails at consistently enforcing this accountability. I think this because 
the government only investigates listings after receiving a complaint, which makes the system dependent 
on others to report issues. One possible change that could improve the system’s accountability could be 
requiring more direct verification of listings before they are allowed to be posted, instead of relying 
mainly on complaints and outside investigations.


As discussed in the introduction, the legality of web scraping is still uncertain in the US.
Skim through the Legal Issues section of Web Scraping in the US on Wikipedia and this
article about the legal issues with the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, and describe at
least one factor you believe is important to consider when discussing the legality of web
scraping and why.

One factor I believe is important to consider when discussing the legality of web scraping is whether 
the data is publicly accessible or restricted. This is so important because even if data is available online, 
websites may still have rules about how that data can be collected and used. Another factor I think is important 
to take into consideration is whether the scraping follows the platform’s specific terms of service because violating 
those terms can create legal issues even if the actual information isn't private.


Scraping public data does not always lead to positive results for society. For example,
look to Facebook–Cambridge Analytica data scandal - Wikipedia or Clearview AI -
Wikipedia. Many argue that using someone’s personal data without their consent (even if
publicly provided) is unethical. Web scraping requires thoughtful intervention. Develop at
least two guidelines you think are important to consider when deciding whether to do
web scraping.

The first guideline I think is important to consider when deciding whether to do web scraping is whether the 
data involves people’s personal information because even if the data is public, using it without people's awareness 
and consent can still be harmful and is not ethical and can create mistrust in the future also. Another important 
guideline is making sure the data is being used for a clear and responsible purpose. Specifically, the data should 
only be used for specifically what it is said it will be used for, nothing additional. This is important because 
scraping should not be used in ways that could negatively impact individuals or misuse their information in any way.
